 complex systems of mass production to assemble extraordinary objects from standardized parts or modules. He reveals how these systems have deep roots in Chinese thought and reflect characteristically Chinese modes of social organization. Combining invaluable aesthetic and cultural insights with a rich variety of illustrations, Ten Thousand Things make a profound statement about Chinese art and society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 7aART / Asian / Chinese.2bisacsh  a.  aBook of Changes (Yijing).  aBuilding Standards (Yingzao fashi).  aEuropean co-invention of.  aJulien, Stanislas.  aLeibniz, Gottfried Wilhelm.  aNan Yue kingdom, tomb of.  aShang module systems in.  aWest, the.  aYijing (Book of Changes).  aYingzao fashi (Building Standards).  aaesthetics of.  aapplied and minor.  aas art form.  aas central to life of literati.  acities, modular-grid layout of.  acollecting of.  acollectors and collecting of.  adevelopments in.  aduring Qin.  aearly trend toward.  aestablishment of European industry for.  afactories (Chinese).  afactory system of production for.  alearning from Chinese art production.  aliteracy (Chinese).  amass production, in China.  amodular production of.  amodular production.  amodularity of.  amodules.  anames of, inscribed on objects.  aperiod.  astandardization.  awall paintings in.  awriting central to life of.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertThe A. W. Mellon Lectures in the Fine Arts eBook Packagez978311129290840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691252889?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691252889423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691252889/original  a978-3-11-129290-8  The A. W. Mellon Lectures in the Fine Arts eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_M